decisions:
  - date: 2026-05-10
    decision: "MCP is now optional (Path A → B)"
    rationale: |
      User goal: maintain only rforge (not also rforge-mcp). Half of MCP's
      13 tools were placeholders; user is single-client (Claude Code, no
      Desktop/Cursor); plugin commands are markdown prompts that work via
      Claude Code's built-in tools without an MCP server.
    path_a_shipped:
      commit: <next>
      changes:
        - "package.json: drop peerDependencies.rforge-mcp"
        - "README.md: reframe Part 1 (MCP install) as optional"
        - "tests/test-plugin-structure.sh: remove Test 8 (peer-dep assertion)"
        - "CHANGELOG.md: document the decoupling in v1.2.0 entry"
    path_b_spec:
      file: docs/specs/SPEC-mcp-absorb-2026-05-10.md
      summary: |
        Migration plan for absorbing rforge-mcp's 7 implemented tools into
        rforge's lib/. 4 phases. Drops 6 placeholder MCP tools entirely.
        Estimated 3-4 sessions, not urgent — A already unblocks npm install.

## 🎯 Next Action

Quick post-release loop on this machine:

A) 🟢 ⚡ **`brew upgrade rforge`** — local install is still at v1.3.0 (Cellar shows /opt/homebrew/Cellar/rforge/1.3.0). `brew info` confirms `1.3.0 → stable 2.0.0` available. ~30s task.

B) 🟢 ⚡ **Phase 2.2 live-test (post-upgrade)** — now feasible from the production install. Fresh `claude` session, type each of the 3 old slash commands, paste outputs into issue #9. ~5 min. Validates the stub format end-to-end and serves as the first feedback data point.

C) 🟡 Watch issue #9 for ~2-4 weeks. No active task; just keep an eye out for rename-ergonomics signal that would inform Phase 4 / v2.1.0 scope.

After A+B done: backlog is the medium-term roadmap below.

---

backlog:
  # Immediate (post-release housekeeping)
  - title: "brew upgrade local rforge install to v2.0.0"
    priority: high
    effort: "< 1 min"
    notes: "`brew upgrade data-wise/tap/rforge`. Local Cellar still at 1.3.0 (the previous version we used for the brew-outdated UX demo). Currently /opt/homebrew/opt/rforge points at 1.3.0 install. After upgrade, /rforge:* slash commands will see the v2.0.0 manifest including rename-error stubs."
  - title: "Phase 2.2 live-test of rename-error stubs (post brew upgrade)"
    priority: high
    effort: "5 min"
    notes: "Carried over from PR #6 review. Now executable from the production v2.0.0 install. Steps: fresh `claude` session → type /rforge:doc-check, /rforge:ecosystem-health, /rforge:rpkg-check → paste verbatim outputs into issue #9 as the first feedback data point. If a stub paraphrases instead of emitting verbatim, file as a v2.0.1 patch."

  # Watch (no active task; passive monitoring)
  - title: "Issue #9 — v2.0.0 rename feedback collection"
    url: https://github.com/Data-Wise/rforge/issues/9
    priority: low
    notes: "Open-ended feedback thread for rename ergonomics + the deferred /rforge:quick + /rforge:thorough rename decision. Watch ~2-4 weeks; decisions inform v2.1.0 scope."

  # Medium-term work (v2.3.0 horizon)
  - title: "Phase 4 — discovery engine + agents (v2.3.0)"
    priority: medium
    notes: "Last craft-parity item. Adds agent definitions mirroring craft's discovery engine. (Bumped from v2.2.0 — that slot was taken by r: CRAN-submission commands.)"

  # Parked (waits on external signal)
  - title: "Path B v1.4.0 — restore 4-mode status contract (descoped from v1.3.0)"
    spec: docs/specs/SPEC-mcp-absorb-2026-05-10.md
    priority: parked
    notes: "lib/status.py shipped as a thin faithful port in v1.3.0. The 4-mode contract (default/debug/optimize/release with R subprocess) was descoped pending real-user input on what depth is wanted. Open a new SPEC when there's demand."

